    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-01T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-01T14:00:00-05:00" n="57"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d57">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/52</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-01T19:00:00+00:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">August 1, 1914, 7 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>Your July 31, 5 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d57fn1">See circular telegram, <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_24">p. 24</ref>
                    </note>. No absolutely conclusive [developments?] but all to-day’s news points
                    to Russia and Germany becoming involved. Communication becomes more difficult
                    from Germany and the telephone from Paris is cut off. Increasing crowds of
                    Americans are flocking from the Continent. The canceling of all German
                    transatlantic ships causes the detention here of many travelers. There will be
                    many cases of want presented to the Embassy forthwith. Have you instructions for
                    their assistance?</p>
                <p>There is yet no financial stringency. Brown Shipley report they can not longer
                    negotiate checks on American or Continental bankers.</p>
                <p>British Admiralty expect a general war and British troops are being concentrated
                    on the North Sea coast.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
